INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('104','Devin Duvernay','Ravens','WR','19.0','215.0','1.0','2.0','15.0','0.0','Baltimore selected Duvernay with a third-round pick during April''s draft. Duvernay (5-foot-10, 200 pounds) is a physical and fast (4.39 40, 4.20 short shuttle) slot receiver with good hands. Granted, he was a short-area target (98% slot, 7.5 aDOT), but Duvernay caught 95% (or 106) of 112 catchable targets at Texas last season, which was easily best in this class. He ranked third in the FBS with 106 receptions. Duvernay has the look of a high-volume short-area target in the pros who can also help as a ball carrier and kick returner. He''ll spend his rookie campaign competing with Marquise Brown, Miles Boykin and Willie Snead for a prominent offensive role in a low-volume Ravens'' pass offense. He''s unlikely to provide much fantasy production in a limited role this season.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('105','Van Jefferson','Rams','WR','18.0','234.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','The Rams selected Jefferson with a second-round pick in April''s draft. Jefferson measures in at 6-foot-1, 200 pounds with good speed, hands (10 career drops on 268 targets) and route-running ability. The Florida product isn''t particularly strong or explosive and struggled to do much with the ball in his hands while operating as a perimeter receiver at Florida. Jones is one of the oldest players in the 2020 draft (he''ll turn 24 this summer), so he''ll be expected to immediately provide competition to Josh Reynolds for No. 3 duties. He''s unlikely to find his way to 2020 fantasy value, barring an injury to Robert Woods or Cooper Kupp, especially with Sean McVay turning to more multiple-tight-end sets down the stretch last season.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('106','Jake Kumerow','Packers','WR','16.0','223.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','No outlook available.');
