INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('135','Marqise Lee','Patriots','WR','8.0','99.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','Lee signed with the Patriots after spending his first six seasons with the Jaguars. He''ll look to get back on track after back-to-back injury-plagued campaigns. The 2014 second-round pick missed all but six games last season after sitting out all of 2018 with a torn ACL. Even when active, Lee was limited to only three receptions on 104 snaps in 2019. He finished in the top 35 among wideouts in targets in both 2016 and 2017, but had more drops (12) than touchdowns (6) during that span. Lee has never finished a season better than WR40 in fantasy and the likes of Julian Edelman, Mohamed Sanu, N''Keal Harry, Jakobi Meyers and Damiere Byrd offer plenty of competition. The 28-year-old is only worth monitoring in deep leagues.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('136','Justin Watson','Buccaneers','WR','7.0','87.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','No outlook available.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('137','J.J. Arcega-Whiteside','Eagles','WR','7.0','91.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','Arcega-Whiteside is back for his second NFL season following an underwhelming rookie campaign. Injuries above him on the depth chart should have positioned the 2019 second-round pick for a generous offensive workload, but instead he was held to 21 targets and a 10-169-1 receiving line on 463 snaps. Clearly not pleased with his progress, the Eagles drafted Jalen Reagor, John Hightower and Quez Watkins, while also acquiring Marquise Goodwin during draft weekend. Given that there''s already Alshon Jeffery, DeSean Jackson and Greg Ward in the fold and Arcega-Whiteside has a very tough path to a second-year breakout. He should be rostered only in dynasty leagues or those very rare "Eagles-only" formats.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('138','Devin Smith','Cowboys','WR','7.0','93.0','1.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','No outlook available.');
INSERT INTO wide_receivers VALUES('139','Gabriel Davis','Bills','WR','7.0','97.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','0.0','The Bills selected Davis in the fourth round of April''s draft. The UCF product checks in at 6-foot-2, 216 pounds with 4.54 wheels. The UCF product was exclusively a perimeter receiver in college, aligning in the slot only 3% of the time over the past two seasons. He caught 125 passes for 2,056 yards and 19 touchdowns during that span, but he also dropped 14 balls. Davis isn''t particularly quick (4.59 short shuttle) and won''t do much after the catch, but he could make some noise as a vertical threat off the bench in the pros. He''s unlikely to get on the field much in 2020 with Stefon Diggs, John Brown and Cole Beasley glued to the starting lineup.');
